<subSubSection id="C34D47CEFFFFC87FFF0DBC03FA4DFD2D" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="357" pageId="1" pageNumber="356" type="key">
<keyStep id="30A30CE0FFFFC87CFF0DBC03FA4DF8DA" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
<paragraph id="8BE81445FFFFC87CFF0DBC03FA4DF972" blockId="1.[151,1437,1624,1793]" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
<keyLead id="30A6B770FFFFC87CFF0DBC03FA4DF972" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
1 Facial edge not or only a little projecting forward beyond the level of the profrons when the head is viewed in profile (
<figureCitation id="136C08C0FFFFC87CFAD0BC03FA40F9B4" box="[1354,1425,1624,1646]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–25" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[237,1344,192,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-38@16.[236,1352,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 22–25. Drymeia setibasis (Huckett). 22. ♂ head, lateral view. 23. ♂ mid femur, anterior view. 24. ♀ mid femur, an- terior view. 25. ♂ hind tibia and tarsomere 1, anterior view. Scale-line 1 mm (3) and 0.5 mm (4–6). (Georgia, Kazbegi, Gergeti, scree &amp; river, 2950–3200 m, 11.vii.1983.)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6538231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6538231/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Scutellum on the lateral margins, below the level of the strong setae, with 5–10 setulae in 1–2 rows. 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFFC87CFB2ABC2DFB14F951" box="[1200,1221,1654,1675]" pageId="1" pageNumber="356" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
: prealar seta absent or short, shorter than 2nd notopleural seta (present in some 
<taxonomicName id="4C576FC6FFFFC87CFC99BCC8FCB1F972" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1780" box="[771,864,1683,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Drymeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="356" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vicana">
<emphasis id="B923C857FFFFC87CFC99BCC8FCB1F972" box="[771,864,1683,1704]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">D. vicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFFC87CFCEEBCC8FC59F972" box="[884,904,1683,1704]" pageId="1" pageNumber="356" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: hind tibia without a posteroventral apical seta..... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE81445FFFFC87CFF0DBCEAFA4DF8DA" blockId="1.[151,1437,1624,1793]" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
<keyLead id="30A6B770FFFFC87CFF0DBCEAFA4DF8DA" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
- Facial edge projecting forward far beyond the level of the profrons when the head is viewed in profile (
<figureCitation id="136C08C0FFFFC87CFB2FBCEBFB2DF91C" box="[1205,1276,1712,1734]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–16" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1886,1910]" captionTargetBox="[206,1381,286,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-57@11.[189,1398,273,1863]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 12–16. Drymeia fratercula sp.nov. 12. ♂ head, lateral view. 13. ♂ hind tibia and tarsomere 1, posterior view. 14. ♀ fore tarsomeres, anterior view. 15. ♂ sternite 5, dorsal view. 16. ♀ tergite 8. Scale-line 0.25 mm (15), 0.5 mm (16). (Georgia, Ka- zbegi, Mt Koltesh, meadow/heath, 2300 m, 8.vii.1983 (12, 13) and 30.vi.1983 (14, 16); Mt Koltesh, heath, 2500 m, 30.vi.1983 (15).)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6538213" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6538213/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Scutellum bare on lateral margins, but with a row of setulae on the ventral surface in 
<taxonomicName id="4C576FC6FFFFC87CFCE4BC95FC29F938" authorityName="Pont" authorityYear="2022" box="[894,1016,1741,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Drymeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="356" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sororcula">
<emphasis id="B923C857FFFFC87CFCE4BC95FC29F938" box="[894,1016,1741,1763]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">D. sororcula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFFC87CFB99BC95FBC9F939" box="[1027,1048,1742,1763]" pageId="1" pageNumber="356" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
: prealar seta present and strong. 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFFC87CFAC9BC95FAB6F939" box="[1363,1383,1742,1763]" pageId="1" pageNumber="356" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: hind tibia with a posteroventral apical seta..................................................................... 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30A30CE0FFFFC87CFF0DBD7EFA4DF86A" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
<paragraph id="8BE81445FFFFC87CFF0DBD7EFA4CF849" blockId="1.[151,1437,1829,2027]" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
<keyLead id="30A6B770FFFFC87CFF0DBD7EFA4CF849" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
2 Anepimeron setulose. Katepimeron with a few short setulae. (
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFFC87CFCA2BD7EFC9BF8E0" box="[824,842,1829,1850]" pageId="1" pageNumber="356" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
with the tip of the abdomen forming a “basket”, with numerous dense setae on the apical margin of tergite 5 and on subsequent tergites, enclosing the genital capsule; mid femur without posteroventral setae except for a group of fine curled setae at base, some longer than femoral depth; hind femur with a row of anteroventral setae in apical half but without posteroventrals except at base).................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C576FC6FFFFC87CFB26BD25FA4CF849" authority="(Schnabl)" baseAuthorityName="Schnabl" box="[1212,1437,1917,1939]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Drymeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="356" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caucasica">
<emphasis id="B923C857FFFFC87CFB26BD25FAE8F849" box="[1212,1337,1918,1939]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">D. caucasica</emphasis>
(Schnabl)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE81445FFFFC87CFF0DBDC0FA4DF86A" blockId="1.[151,1437,1829,2027]" box="[151,1436,1947,1969]" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
<keyLead id="30A6B770FFFFC87CFF0DBDC0FA4DF86A" box="[151,1436,1947,1969]" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">- Anepimeron bare. Katepimeron bare...................................................................... 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30A30CE0FFFFC87FFF0DBDE3FA4DFEDF" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="357" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
<paragraph id="8BE81445FFFFC87FFF0DBDE3FA4CFF77" blockId="1.[151,1437,1829,2027]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,261]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="357" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
<keyLead id="30A6B770FFFFC87FFF0DBDE3FA4CFF77" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="357" pageId="1" pageNumber="356">
3 Eyes densely haired, less conspicuously so in female. 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFFC87CFD68BDE2FCD6F814" box="[754,775,1977,1998]" pageId="1" pageNumber="356" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
: fore leg with no posteroventral setulae at apex of tarsomere 1; mid femur with complete rows of fine anteroventral and posteroventral setae, the posteroventrals longer; hind femur with complete rows of anteroventral and posteroventral setae................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C576FC6FFFCC87FFB77BAC3FA4CFF77" authority="(Harris)" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1780" box="[1261,1437,151,173]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Drymeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vicana">
<emphasis id="B923C857FFFCC87FFB77BAC3FA9BFF77" box="[1261,1354,152,173]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">D. vicana</emphasis>
(Harris)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE81445FFFCC87FFF0DBAEEFA4DFEDF" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,261]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
<keyLead id="30A6B770FFFCC87FFF0DBAEEFA4DFEDF" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
- Eyes bare. 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFCC87FFED1BAEEFEB1FF10" box="[331,352,181,202]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
: fore tarsomere 1 with several long posteroventral setulae near apex; mid femur without posteroventral setae, and without anteroventrals except for some long, bent setae on basal quarter and some long anterior setae above them (
<figureCitation id="136C08C0FFFCC87FFAA2BA89FA40FF32" box="[1336,1425,210,232]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 3–4" captionStart-1="FIGURES 5–7" captionStartId-0="6.[151,262,1971,1995]" captionStartId-1="7.[151,262,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox-0="[340,1248,345,1929]" captionTargetBox-1="[450,1142,225,1908]" captionTargetId-0="figure-103@6.[340,1248,345,1948]" captionTargetId-1="figure-17@7.[425,1163,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId-0="6" captionTargetPageId-1="7" captionText-0="FIGURES 3–4. Drymeia fasciculata (Stein), ♂ habitus. 3. Lateral view. 4. Dorsal view. (Georgia, Kazbegi, Mt Sameba, pasture, 2250–2300 m, 2.vii.1983.)" captionText-1="FIGURES 5–7. Drymeia fasciculata (Stein). 5. ♂ mid femur, anterior view. 6. ♀ mid femur, anterior view. 7. ♂ sternite 5, dorsal view. Scale line 0.25 mm. (Azerbaijan.)" figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6538205" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6538207" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6538205/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6538207/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">Figs 4–5</figureCitation>
); hind femur with anteroventral setae in apical half but without posteroventrals..................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C576FC6FFFCC87FFB50BAABFA4DFEDF" authority="(Huckett)" baseAuthorityName="Huckett" baseAuthorityYear="1965" box="[1226,1436,239,261]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Drymeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setibasis">
<emphasis id="B923C857FFFCC87FFB50BAABFAEAFEDE" box="[1226,1339,239,261]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">D. setibasis</emphasis>
(Huckett)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30A30CE0FFFCC87FFF0DBB71FA4DFE09" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
<paragraph id="8BE81445FFFCC87FFF0DBB71FA4DFE4D" blockId="2.[151,1437,298,467]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
<keyLead id="30A6B770FFFCC87FFF0DBB71FA4DFE4D" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
4 Parafacial very broad, at middle almost twice as wide as width of postpedicel (
<figureCitation id="136C08C0FFFCC87FFC43BB71FBF3FE9A" box="[985,1058,298,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–16" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1886,1910]" captionTargetBox="[206,1381,286,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-57@11.[189,1398,273,1863]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 12–16. Drymeia fratercula sp.nov. 12. ♂ head, lateral view. 13. ♂ hind tibia and tarsomere 1, posterior view. 14. ♀ fore tarsomeres, anterior view. 15. ♂ sternite 5, dorsal view. 16. ♀ tergite 8. Scale-line 0.25 mm (15), 0.5 mm (16). (Georgia, Ka- zbegi, Mt Koltesh, meadow/heath, 2300 m, 8.vii.1983 (12, 13) and 30.vi.1983 (14, 16); Mt Koltesh, heath, 2500 m, 30.vi.1983 (15).)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6538213" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6538213/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Face with a prominent snout between the base of the antennae. (3 postsutural dorsocentrals.) 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFCC87FFD6ABB13FCD4FE87" box="[752,773,328,349]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
: hind tibia with a posteroventral apical seta, but with no prolongation of the apex of the tibia to form a short spur (
<figureCitation id="136C08C0FFFCC87FFD17BB3EFD04FEA1" box="[653,725,357,379]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–16" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1886,1910]" captionTargetBox="[206,1381,286,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-57@11.[189,1398,273,1863]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 12–16. Drymeia fratercula sp.nov. 12. ♂ head, lateral view. 13. ♂ hind tibia and tarsomere 1, posterior view. 14. ♀ fore tarsomeres, anterior view. 15. ♂ sternite 5, dorsal view. 16. ♀ tergite 8. Scale-line 0.25 mm (15), 0.5 mm (16). (Georgia, Ka- zbegi, Mt Koltesh, meadow/heath, 2300 m, 8.vii.1983 (12, 13) and 30.vi.1983 (14, 16); Mt Koltesh, heath, 2500 m, 30.vi.1983 (15).)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6538213" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6538213/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). (
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFCC87FFD74BB3EFCD1FEA0" box="[750,768,357,378]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
with complete rows of anteroventral and posteroventral setae on mid femur and hind femur, these rows also complete but sparser in the 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFCC87FFCFABBD8FCA1FE42" box="[864,880,387,408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
)............................ 
<emphasis id="B923C857FFFCC87FFB4ABBD9FA4DFE4D" bold="true" box="[1232,1436,386,408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
<taxonomicName id="4C576FC6FFFCC87FFB4ABBD9FA81FE42" authority="Pont, 2022" authorityName="Pont" authorityYear="2022" box="[1232,1360,386,408]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Drymeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fratercula" status="sp.nov.">
<emphasis id="B923C857FFFCC87FFB4ABBD9FA81FE42" bold="true" box="[1232,1360,386,408]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">D. fratercula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A210752CFFFCC87FFACCBBD9FA4DFE4D" box="[1366,1436,386,407]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" rank="species">sp.nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE81445FFFCC87FFF0DBBFBFA4DFE09" blockId="2.[151,1437,298,467]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
<keyLead id="30A6B770FFFCC87FFF0DBBFBFA4DFE09" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
- Parafacial narrower, at middle equal to width of postpedicel (
<figureCitation id="136C08C0FFFCC87FFCB2BBC4FCBEFE6C" box="[808,879,415,438]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–35" captionStartId="23.[151,262,1472,1496]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1440]" captionTargetId="figure-17@23.[164,1423,181,1448]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 33–35. Drymeia sororcula sp. nov. 33. ♂ head, lateral view. 34. ♀ fore tarsomeres, posterior view. 35. ♂ sternite 5, dorsal view. Scale line 0.25 mm. (Georgia, Kazbegi, Mt Kuro, heath, 2120–2330 m, 29.vi.1983 (33, 35), Mt Koltesh, meadows, 2000–2100 m, 8.vii.1983 (34).)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6538250" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6538250/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
). Face without a snout between the antennae. 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFCC87FFAB9BBFBFAE9FE6F" box="[1315,1336,416,437]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
: hind tibia without a posteroventral apical seta, but with a ventral spur-like prolongation of the apex of the tibia................... 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30A30CE0FFFCC87FFF0DBBACFA4DFD2D" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
<paragraph id="8BE81445FFFCC87FFF0DBBACFA4CFD59" blockId="2.[151,1437,503,760]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
<keyLead id="30A6B770FFFCC87FFF0DBBACFA4CFD59" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
5 4 postsutural dorsocentral setae. Scutellum bare on ventral surface.Anepimeron always bare. 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFCC87FFBC6BBA3FBA0FDD7" box="[1116,1137,504,525]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
: mid femur with the anteroventral setae restricted to a group of 5–6 setae in apical fifth, and with posteroventral setae in basal two-thirds (
<figureCitation id="136C08C0FFFCC87FFB7FB84EFAF1FDF1" box="[1253,1312,533,555]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–7" captionStartId="7.[151,262,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[450,1142,225,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[425,1163,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 5–7. Drymeia fasciculata (Stein). 5. ♂ mid femur, anterior view. 6. ♀ mid femur, anterior view. 7. ♂ sternite 5, dorsal view. Scale line 0.25 mm. (Azerbaijan.)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6538207" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6538207/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); hind femur with a complete row of anteroventrals, but with no posteroventrals. 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFCC87FFCEBB868FC54FD92" box="[881,901,563,584]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: parafacial with a shining patch at the level of antennal insertion; mid femur with a few posteroventral setae in basal half, and with 2–3 anteroventrals before apex and, sometimes, a further seta near base of femur (
<figureCitation id="136C08C0FFFCC87FFD8FB836FD81FD59" box="[533,592,621,643]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–7" captionStartId="7.[151,262,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[450,1142,225,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[425,1163,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 5–7. Drymeia fasciculata (Stein). 5. ♂ mid femur, anterior view. 6. ♀ mid femur, anterior view. 7. ♂ sternite 5, dorsal view. Scale line 0.25 mm. (Azerbaijan.)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6538207" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6538207/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); hind femur with a complete anteroventral row as in 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFCC87FFBCEB836FBB7FD58" box="[1108,1126,621,642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
....... 
<taxonomicName id="4C576FC6FFFCC87FFB54B835FA4CFD59" authority="(Stein)" baseAuthorityName="Stein" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[1230,1437,621,643]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Drymeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciculata">
<emphasis id="B923C857FFFCC87FFB54B835FA84FD58" box="[1230,1365,621,643]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">D. fasciculata</emphasis>
(Stein)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE81445FFFCC87FFF0DB8D0FA4DFD2D" blockId="2.[151,1437,503,760]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
<keyLead id="30A6B770FFFCC87FFF0DB8D0FA4DFD2D" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
- 3 postsutural dorsocentral setae. Scutellum with several strong setulae on ventral surface.Anepimeron often with a few setulae. 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFCC87FFF78B8F3FF26FD67" box="[226,247,680,701]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
: mid and hind femora each with complete rows of anteroventral and posteroventral setae. 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFCC87FFBF6B8F3FB51FD67" box="[1132,1152,680,701]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: parafacial without a shining patch in upper part; mid femur without posteroventral setae, on anteroventral surface with 1 seta near base and 2 very short, almost spinulose setae just before apex; hind femur with a sparse row of anteroventrals.............. 
<emphasis id="B923C857FFFCC87FFB49B8B9FA4DFD2D" bold="true" box="[1235,1436,738,760]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
<taxonomicName id="4C576FC6FFFCC87FFB49B8B9FA81FD22" authority="Pont, 2022" authorityName="Pont" authorityYear="2022" box="[1235,1360,738,760]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Drymeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sororcula" status="sp.nov.">
<emphasis id="B923C857FFFCC87FFB49B8B9FA81FD22" bold="true" box="[1235,1360,738,760]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">D. sororcula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A210752CFFFCC87FFACCB8B9FA4DFD2D" box="[1366,1436,738,759]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" rank="species">sp.nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
